'''''Alger républicain''''' (''Republican Algeria'', الجزائر الجمهورية) is an [[Arabic language]] [[Algeria]]n [[List of newspapers in Algeria|newspaper]] published in [[Algeria]].
==History and profile== ''Alger républicain'' was founded in October 1938,<ref name=mark>{{cite book|author=Mark Orme|title=The Development of Albert Camus's Concern for Social and Political Justice: "justice Pour Un Juste"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VGBSVdHwmUYC&pg=PA66|accessdate=11 September 2014|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8386-4110-1|page=66}}</ref> and intermittently published ever since. In its initial phase the paper declared itself as "the honest newspaper of the honest people".<ref name=mark/> It is close to the [[Algerian Communist Party|Algerian communist movement]], without having been an official party publication. However, the movement controlled the paper in the past.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Ottaway|author2=Marina Ottaway|title=Algeria: The Politics of a Socialist Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bp8IfVxOcEQC&pg=PA183|accessdate=11 September 2014|date=1 January 1970|publisher=University of California Press|page=183|id=GGKEY:TN91X5AFRUD}}</ref>
The paper was edited by the French-Algerian communist and anti-colonial activist [[Henri Alleg]] from 1951, as a major daily newspaper. Despite censorship and confiscation of copies by the French authorities, it had become perhaps the largest daily in Algeria at independence in 1962, having featured a number of prominent writers and journalists, including [[Albert Camus]] and [[Kateb Yacine]]. Alger républicain was banned in 1965 by the government of [[Houari Boumédiène]], but later refounded by Alleg and others in exile. In 1994, it ceased regular publication, but has since returned under Alleg's editorship, and is now on sale in Algeria again.
