The '''Berlin–Munich high-speed railway''' is a roughly {{convert|623|km|abbr=on}} long [[High-speed rail|High-speed railway line]] between the [[Germany|German]] cities of [[Berlin]], [[Nuremberg]], [[Erfurt]], [[Leipzig]] and [[Munich]]. The line was opened on 10 December 2017.<ref name="thelocal">{{cite web|title=Opening of new Berlin-Munich high-speed train line to be celebrated Friday|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20171206/opening-of-new-berlin-munich-high-speed-train-line-to-celebrate-with-merkel|author=|journal=[[The Local]]|date=6 December 2017}}</ref> The line was first planned in 1991 as part of the "Travel Project for German Unity" - a scheme of linking up east and west German travel infrastructure after [[Reunification of Germany|reunification]].<ref name="thelocal"/> Construction began in 1996 and the cost of the project has been about €10 billion ($11.8 billion),<ref name="DW">{{cite web|title=Berlin-Munich high-speed train line to be opened|url=http://www.dw.com/en/berlin-munich-high-speed-train-line-to-be-opened/g-41688949|author=|journal=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=7 December 2017}}</ref> making it the most expensive transport project in Germany since reunification.<ref name="spiegel">{{cite web|title=Billions Upon Billions for Berlin-Munich Bullet Train|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/germany-s-longest-subway-billions-upon-billions-for-berlin-munich-bullet-train-a-794125.html|author=Christian Wüst|journal=[[Spiegel Online]]|date=27 October 2011}}</ref> The service was plagued by delays in its first week of operation and [[Deutsche Bahn]] cancelled several services.<ref name="irj">{{cite web|title=Difficult first week for new German HS line|url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/europe/difficult-first-week-for-new-german-hs-line.html?channel=537|author=Keith Fender|journal=[[International Railway Journal]]|date=15 December 2017}}</ref>

