{{Infobox beverage | name = Bäsk | image = Artemisia absinthium 0002.JPG | caption = ''[[Artemisia absinthium]]'' is used to make bäsk and other liquors | type = Liquor | abv = | proof = | manufacturer = Jeppson's Malört | distributor = | origin = Sweden | introduced = | discontinued = | colour = | flavour = | ingredients = Wormwood | variants = | related = | website = | region = }}
{{Redirect|Malort|the American liquor brand|Jeppson's Malört}} {{Unreferenced|date=January 2013}}
'''Bäsk''' (Swedish for "bitter") is a [[Alcoholic beverages in Sweden|Swedish]] style spiced [[Brännvin|liquor]] flavored with [[Artemisia absinthium|wormwood]] ("malört" in [[Swedish language|Swedish]]). [[Sweden]] is one of the few countries that have never banned [[absinthe]] or other wormwood-flavored liquors.
In the United States, the [[Chicago]]-based brand [[Jeppson's Malört]] is one of the most well-known versions of the liquor.
Bäsk is said to be [[digestif|good for]] [[digestion]], and therefore is traditionally associated with fatty foods.
