{{Infobox radio station | image = 97.5 Virgin Radio logo.svg| name = CIQM-FM| airdate = 1986 (at 103.1 FM) | frequency = 97.5 [[Megahertz|MHz]] ([[FM radio|FM]]) | city = [[London, Ontario]]| format = [[Contemporary hit radio|CHR]] | owner = [[Bell Media]] | licensee = [[Bell Media Radio]] | erp = 50,000 [[watt]]s | haat = {{convert|141|meters}}| branding = 97.5 Virgin Radio | slogan = ''London's #1 Hit Music Station''| class = B | webcast = [http://ciqm.player.amri.ca/ Listen Live] | website = [http://london.virginradio.ca/ london.virginradio.ca] | callsign_meaning = | former_frequencies = 103.1 MHz (1986-1993) | sister_stations = [[CJBK]], [[CJBX-FM]] | }}
'''CIQM-FM''' is an [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] broadcasting at 97.5 FM in [[London, Ontario]], Canada, branded as '''97-5 [[Virgin Radio]]'''. The station airs a [[contemporary hit radio|CHR]] format. CIQM is owned by [[Bell Media]] and its sister stations include [[CJBX-FM|CJBX]], and [[CJBK]]. CIQM's studios are at 743 Wellington Road while its transmitter is located near Byron in West London
CIQM operates on a frequency once occupied by [[CKO]] from 1977 to 1989.
== History == CIQM originally operated as "Q103" at 103.1 FM (now the home of [[CFHK-FM]] in St. Thomas) from its sign-on in 1986 <ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/1986/DB86-19.HTM Decision CRTC 86-19]</ref> until moving to the 97.5 frequency vacated by CKO in 1993.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/1993/DB93-20.htm Decision CRTC 93-20]</ref> For many years, the station was known as "Q97.5," even after taking on the "[[EZ Rock]]" trademark; in [[2006 in radio|2006]], the "Q" was dropped and the station became known as simply "97.5, London's EZ Rock."
[[File:CIQM FM.png|thumb|EZ Rock logo 2010-2012]] On September 6, 2010, CIQM underwent several changes, including a tweak in branding (as "The New Sound of EZ Rock"), a new logo and new on-air staff. The station moved from its 24-year-old [[adult contemporary]] format to [[hot adult contemporary]]. The switch was due to rival [[CKOT-FM]] switching from [[easy listening]] to a gold-based [[Soft AC]] mix, and also because of rimshot rivals [[CIHR-FM]] and [[CHGK-FM]], both mainstream AC stations, also being heard in London. The station also dropped the decimal point from the station ID after flipping to [[Hot AC]]. Just after the format tweak, Astral switched CIQM's jingles from the [[adult hits]] jingles to the [[hot adult contemporary]] jingles. Despite all of the changes, CIQM, which once dominated the market, suffered from ratings erosion, and had the lowest share in the London CMA, and was a distant second place behind CKOT.
On August 13, 2012, CIQM began stunting with jockless music, as well as their website being replaced by a countdown clock, informing listeners to tune in August 17 at 8 AM. At that time, the station flipped to [[contemporary hit radio|CHR]], becoming the 5th station in Canada (10th overall, including [[CKQB-FM|CKQB]] in [[Ottawa]], although that station reverted to its previous "Bear" branding (and has since flipped to CHR), [[CKZZ-FM|CKZZ]] in [[Vancouver]] (though they are considered Hot AC, and has since reverted to its former "Z95.3" branding), and [[CFBT-FM|CFBT]] in Vancouver) using the "Virgin Radio" branding. The final song on '''EZ Rock''' was "[[Rehab (Amy Winehouse song)|Rehab]]" by [[Amy Winehouse]], while the first song on '''Virgin Radio''' was "[[Pound The Alarm]]" by [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/69607/ez-rock-stunting-in-london/</ref><ref>http://formatchange.com/ezrock-becomes-virgin-radio/</ref> The station has a full-time air staff, as well as the London affiliate for [[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]. Longtime rival [[CFHK-FM|CFHK]] became once again the market's only [[hot adult contemporary]] station. CIQM-FM's flip to [[contemporary hit radio]] filled the Top 40 void in London for the first time since 2004, when CFHK dropped it in favour of its current Hot AC format.
As part of Astral's merger with [[Bell Media]] on June 27, 2013, CIQM is now owned by Bell Media.
