[[File:Peixinhos da horta.jpg|thumb|A plate of ''Peixinhos da horta'']]
{{lang|pt|'''Peixinhos da horta'''}} ({{IPA-pt|pɐjˈʃĩɲuʒ}} or {{IPA-pt|pejˈʃĩɲuʒ ðɐ ˈɔɾtɐ|}}) is a traditional dish in [[Portuguese cuisine]]. The name of the dish is literally translated as "Little fishes from the garden", as it resembles small pieces of colorful fish.<ref>[http://www.cm-lisboa.pt/en/visit/flavours-of-lisboa/peixinhos-da-horta-deep-fried-green-beans Peixinhos da Horta]</ref> It was introduced to [[Japan]] by Jesuit missionaries in the sixteenth century, where it was eventually developed into [[tempura]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=30uhs5rPpXEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Everybody's+San+Francisco+Cookbook#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=240|title=Everybody's San Francisco Cookbook|author = Charles Lemos |publisher= Good Life Publications|year= 1998 | isbn=978-1-886776-01-2 |accessdate = 22 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="tempura origins">{{cite web|url=http://www.kikkoman.com/foodforum/thejapanesetablebackissues/06.shtml|work=[[Kikkoman|The World of Kikkoman]]|title=Tracking Down Tempura|author=Morieda, Takashi|accessdate=2007-12-13|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110233636/http://www.kikkoman.com/foodforum/thejapanesetablebackissues/06.shtml|archivedate=2008-01-10|df=}}</ref>

==Preparation==
''Peixinhos da horta'' is usually prepared with [[green bean]]s in a wheat flour based batter that are then deep fried.<ref>{{cite book   | title = La Cucina Portoghese. Ediz. Inglese | author= S. Cunningham Dryburgh (translator)  |publisher = Casa Editrice Bonechi | location=   |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=DNiSuNvBAD4C&pg=PA4&dq=Peixinhos+da+horta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjY9uHyndXLAhVC1mMKHfnqDB04ChDoAQgmMAI#v=onepage&q=Peixinhos%20da%20horta&f=false | date = 2002  | page =  17 | isbn = 9788847609211 | accessdate = 22 March 2016}}</ref> Other vegetables such as [[bell pepper]]s and [[Squash (plant)|squash]] are also used.

